question:
Let $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & -1 & 0 \\ 
0 & 1 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$  and $C=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
1  & 0 \\ 
2 & -1 \\
0  & 1 \end{array}
\right)$. Which of the following statements is correct?

Consider $A=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$ and  $B=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
a & b \\ 
c & d \end{array}
\right)$. If $A$ commutes with $B$, (AB = BA) then which of the following statements is correct?

Find $x$ and $y$ such that $\left( \begin{array}{rr}
-2 & 1 \\ 
3 & -4 \end{array}
\right)\left( \begin{array}{rr}
x & 2 \\ 
1 & y \end{array}
\right)=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
-3 & 1 \\ 
2 & -14 \end{array}
\right)$.

Let $M=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
1  & 0 & 2 \\ 
-1 & 1 & 0\\
0  & 2 & 1\end{array}
\right)$ and $f(x)=x^2-2x+3$. Find $f(M).$

Suppose that $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 0 & -1 \\ 
3 & 1 & 0 \\ 
-2 & 1 & 3 \end{array}
\right)$.

Find matrix $B$ such that matrices $A$ and $B$ are inverses.

Let $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & -1 & 0 \\ 
0 & 1 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$  and $C=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
1  & 0 \\ 
2 & -1 \\
0  & 1 \end{array}
\right)$. Which of the following statements is correct?

Suppose that $A=\left( 
 \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 1 & 3 \\ 
0 & 0 & 5  \\ 
-1 & -2 & 1  \\ 
3 & 1 & 2 \end{array} \right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 1 & 0 \\ 
2 & 1 & 1 \\ 
1 & 1 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$, and $C=\left(  \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 2 & 0  \\ 
2 & 4 & 1  \\ 
3 & 6 & 2  \\ 
-4 & -8 & 1  \end{array}
\right)$.

Which matrix has the rank $2$ ?
